PISA presentation¶

by Aldana Rodríguez¶

Investigation Overview¶

The overall goal of my presentation is to show what factors affects a child's grade.

Dataset Overview¶

For this I used the PISA dataset. PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education.

Note that the above cells have been set as "Skip"-type slides. That means that when the notebook is rendered as http slides, those cells won't show up.

Wealth against grade¶

There is a clear trend upwards. Wealthier children tend to be in a higher school grade even though they are all the same age.

Math, reading and science grades against wealth¶

In all three cases there is a clear upwards trend. Wealthier children do better in math, reading and science subjects.

Math, reading and science grades against mathematical anxiety¶

Anxious children, on the other hand, do worse the more anxious they are.

Math, reading and science grades against father's schooling¶

The more educated the father is, the better the child does in all subjects.

Math, reading and science grades against mother's schooling¶

The same happens with the mother's education.

Grid of math, reading and science grades¶

Also, and not surprisingly, children that do better at one subject tend to do better at the other subjects as well.
